          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Isoelectric Focussing</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A patient with a known history of diabetes mellitus presents to the outpatient department for a routine follow-up appointment after three months. As part of the management and monitoring plan, the healthcare provider requests an HbA1c test, which is crucial for assessing long-term glycemic control. Considering the various methods available for HbA1c estimation, which of the following is considered the most accurate and reliable method?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4503844",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29852,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) High performance liquid chromatography&nbsp; </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">There are more than <strong>30 different methods </strong>for the determination of <strong>Glyc Hbs</strong>. It includes : </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"1\" style=\"list-style-type:lower-roman\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Based on charge differences</strong> (ion-exchange chromatography, HPLC, electrophoresis, and isoelectric focusing), </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Structural differences </strong>(affinity chromatography and immunoassay)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Chemical analysis</strong> (photometry and spectrophotometry) </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Mass</strong> (mass spectrometry). </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">NOTE - <strong>Ion Exchange Chromatography</strong> is a <strong>modified HPLC</strong> which is used for <strong>HbA1C estimation.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Affinity chromatography:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> While affinity chromatography can be used for <strong>HbA1c measurement,</strong> it is <strong>not as specific </strong>or as <strong>widely</strong> used as <strong>HPLC. </strong>It relies on the <strong>specific binding of HbA1c </strong>to a particular substrate, which can be influenced by the <strong>presence of</strong> <strong>hemoglobin variants.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.&nbsp; Electrophoresis:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Electrophoresis can separate <strong>different hemoglobin types </strong>based on their <strong>electric charge,</strong> but it is <strong>less</strong> precise than<strong> HPLC for quantifying HbA1c levels</strong> and can be <strong>affected</strong> by the <strong>presence of hemoglobin variants.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Isoelectric focusing:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This technique separates <strong>proteins based</strong> on their <strong>isoelectric </strong>points. While it can differentiate various <strong>hemoglobin forms</strong>, it is<strong> not</strong> the preferred method for <strong>routine HbA1c estimation</strong> due to <strong>its complexity</strong> and the <strong>difficulty</strong> in <strong>quantification.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>High-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC)</strong> is <strong>widely</strong> recognized as the <strong>gold standard for HbA1c estimation </strong>due to its<strong> accuracy, reliability, and reproducibility</strong>. <strong>HPLC </strong>separates various forms of <strong>hemoglobin, including HbA1c, </strong>based on <strong>their charge and size </strong>under <strong>high pressure</strong>, allowing for <strong>precise quantification. </strong>This method <strong>minimizes interference from hemoglobin variants </strong>and provides a<strong> clear, specific measurement of HbA1c levels</strong>, which reflect the <strong>average blood glucose concentration </strong>over the <strong>previous 2-3 months.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Tietz fundamentals of Clinical Chemistry, 6th edition, page 396</span></strong></span></span></p>",
